{
  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework called 'Learnable Multi-Hop Selection with Dynamic Relevance Graphs' (LMS-DRG) for iterative context filtering in multi-turn dialogue systems. The central idea is to model the conversation history as a dynamic graph where utterances are nodes and weighted directed edges represent contextual relevance or inferential dependency. At each hop, a graph neural network (GNN) updates node embeddings and edge weights based on current relevance estimates, while a reinforcement learning (RL)-guided selector prunes less influential nodes and strengthens critical paths. Unlike static selection mechanisms, our model allows the graph topology to evolve across hops, enabling the system to focus on increasingly refined substructures of the dialogue history.\n\nA key innovation is the integration of a lightweight generator module that, at each hop, produces a tentative response embedding based on the current context subgraph. This generated hypothesis is then used to compute a grounding score with the actual candidate response, forming a 'generate-and-ground' signal that guides the next round of graph refinement. This mimics the GenGround paradigm but operates within the dialogue context rather than document retrieval, allowing the model to test and revise its understanding of relevance iteratively.\n\nThe selector operates as a differentiable sparsification layer, trained jointly with the matcher using policy gradients to maximize response ranking performance. It learns to balance completeness and conciseness—retaining enough context for accurate matching while minimizing noise. We further introduce a diversity regularization term to encourage exploration of alternative reasoning paths, avoiding premature convergence to suboptimal subsets.\n\nThis framework addresses limitations in existing methods: unlike MSN (Paper 1), which uses fixed-hop attention, our model adapts its reasoning depth per instance; unlike MCMH (Paper 2), which focuses on symbolic knowledge graphs, we apply multi-chain reasoning over natural language utterances; and unlike GenGround (Paper 3), we do not rely on external corpora but instead ground internal hypotheses against dialogue context. The result is a more adaptive, interpretable, and noise-resilient mechanism for response selection.\n\nPotential impact includes improved robustness in long, topic-shifting dialogues, better explainability via visualizable relevance graphs, and a new paradigm for iterative reasoning in conversational AI. The model could serve as a plug-in module for existing architectures like Poly-Encoder or ColBERT, enhancing their contextual focus without sacrificing expressiveness.",
