ymbolic knowledge graphs, we apply multi-chain reasoning over natural language utterances; and unlike GenGround (Paper 3), we do not rely on external corpora but instead ground internal hypotheses against dialogue context. The result is a more adaptive, interpretable, and noise-resilient mechanism for response selection.\n\nPotential impact includes improved robustness in long, topic-shifting dialogues, better explainability via visualizable relevance graphs, and a new paradigm for iterative reasoning in conversational AI. The model could serve as a plug-in module for existing architectures like Poly-Encoder or ColBERT, enhancing their contextual focus without sacrificing expressiveness.",
